deck_excerpt: A guide on the STRONGEST fusion deck Yugioh has to offer - Chimera Branded! Turbo out beast/fiend floodgates from deck! >:3
deck_description:
Branded Chimera is arguably the strongest fusion deck currently available in TCG Yugioh right now. Branded isn't a one trick pony anymore that HAS to resolve Branded Fusion - it can do that and much more with the Chimera cards! With the support from AGOV, Branded Chimera boards can end on Mirrorjade's banish, set quick-fusion spells, fiend/beast floodgates, a packed GY full of follow-up, and 3-5+ cards in hand! The deck also is chock full of one-card combos meaning both Branded and Chimera packages are compact, allowing the duelist to fit in a plethora of staples in their deck.  
 
This guide partly takes inspiration from TCGPlayer's article entitled "New Combos And Tech Cards For Chimera Fusion." Be sure to check out their article as well!
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
As the name implies, Branded Chimera is composed of the two archetypes. Within two compact fusion engines lies a plethora of powerful plays that are highly searchable 1 card combos! 
 
CHIMERA is an incredible advantage deck core capable of overwhelming your opponent with so much resources, interactions and draw power - all in one fusion strategy! For example, one Mirror Swordknight is a whopping +7 in card advantage! CHIMERA creates is a simple and solid gameplan in itself with it's boss monsters - Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts and Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts. While they are on the field, their names are "Chimera the Flying Mythical Beast." In the GY, Mirror Swordknight and Cornfield Coatl (sent to the GY as part of the combo) offer some targeting protection (Coatl) and monster effect negation (Swordknight). Berfomet and Gazelle nab resources from deck when summoned and used as fusion material. The deck's fusion card, Chimera Fusion, recurs itself from the GY if Chimera the Flying Mythical Beast is on the field or GY (which is always the case). Everything in this archetype grabs resources and recurs itself in this deck so you can keep fusion summoning and interrupting your opponent! 
 
BRANDED in this strategy isn't the main focus - it is merely a support engine designed to increase the consistency of and power of Chimera. Branded Fusion is primarily used to fuse into Rindbrumm using Albaz and Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws, netting you an Illusion monster from deck. This starts your Chimera combo! A mini Despia engine is included with 2 Branded Opening and 1 Aluber for a total of 5 ways to access Branded Fusion without using your normal summon. 
 
Since both archetypes are so compact, this deck is chock full of STAPLES! These staples can be exchanged for other cards as needed in games 2/3. 42 cards are used in this deck since the starters for both decks are highly searchable and are 1-card combos. Card count being slightly above 40 also reduces the chance for the duelist to hard draw garnets like Albaz and End of Anubis. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Previously, Branded Chimera had the usual strategy of deploying multiple fusion boss monsters backed by a robust gameplan and grindgame. With AGOV support, in particular "Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts'," foolish burial effect for any fiend, beast or illusion, the deck has more options and additional win conditions! For example, with Berfomet's "search" of infamous fiend floodgates like "End of Anubis" and "Chaos Hunter" by sending them to the GY and with Sanctifire/Chimera King's monster reborn effect - you can immediately lock your opponent out of the game! As a result, the infamous "Puppet Lock" style play that Branded infamously does has become more accessible, consistent and safe with Branded Chimera's new cards. 
 
With that being said, here are Branded Chimera's main combos: 

You may notice in the side deck there are various fiend and fiend floodgates. End of Anubis shuts down Unchained and Tearlaments. King Tiger Wanghu destroys decks with low ATK monsters such as Floowandereeze and Spright. Chaos Hunter stops Dragonlink and Runick! Now with a singular Mirror Swordknight, these floodgates are easily searchable and summonable! 
 
Mirror Swordknight = Floodgate of choice (Lets use End of Anubis for this example) + a lot of resources/follow-up + Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts + 1 hand-rip + monster negate (Swordknight in GY) + targeting protection (Cornfield Coatl in GY). 
  1. Normal summon Mirror Swordknight. 
  2. Activate Mirror Swordknight's effect to summon Big-Winged Berfomet from deck.
  3. On summon, Big-Winged Berfomet searches for Chimera Fusion and Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws. 
  4. Activate Chimera Fusion to fusion summon Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts using Big-Winged Berfomet + Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws. 
  5. CL1 Big-Winged Berfomet to summon from GY Mirror Swordknight, CL2 Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws to search from deck any Illusion monster, CL3 Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts to send a random card from opponent's hand to the GY in the End Phase. 
  6. Activate Chimera Fusion in the GY to add it to your hand. 
  7. Activate Chimera Fusion to fusion summon Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts by fusing Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts + any Beast, Fiend or Illusion. 
  8. On summon, Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts sends to GY your target of choice (for this example let's use End of Anubis). 
  9. During your end phase, resolve Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts' effect to send 1 random card for your opponent's hand to the GY.
  10. During your opponent's draw phase (or whenever you feel like it's best), activate Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts' effect to summon End of Anubis from the GY. 
Congrats! With a singular card you've locked your opponent out from playing the game! 
 
The next combo involves Branded Fusion and with siding in a lingering floodgate, D/D Orthros. (This strategy can be maindecked, but this is better going 1st IMO).
 
Mirror Swordknight + Branded Fusion = fiend-lock for your opponent (D/D Orthros) + a lot of resources/follow-up + Albion the Sanctifire Dragon + Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts + 1 hand-rip + monster negate (Swordknight in GY) + targeting protection (Cornfield Coatl in GY). 
  1. Normal summon Mirror Swordknight. 
  2. Activate Mirror Swordknight's effect to summon Big-Winged Berfomet from deck.
  3. On summon, Big-Winged Berfomet searches for Chimera Fusion and Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws. 
  4. Activate Chimera Fusion to fusion summon Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts using Big-Winged Berfomet + Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws. 
  5. CL1 Big-Winged Berfomet to summon from GY Mirror Swordknight, CL2 Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws to search from deck any Illusion monster, CL3 Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts to send a random card from opponent's hand to the GY in the End Phase. 
  6. Activate Chimera Fusion in the GY to add it to your hand. 
  7. Activate Chimera Fusion to fusion summon Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts by fusing Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts + any Beast, Fiend or Illusion. 
  8. On summon, Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts sends to GY D/D Orthros (Or whatever target you'll summon with Sanctifire). 
  9. Activate Branded Fusion to fusion summon Albion The Sanctifire Dragon by sending Albaz + Light Spellcaster (usually Effect Veiler but it can also be Cartesia) from deck to GY. 
  10. During your end phase, resolve Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts' effect to send 1 random card for your opponent's hand to the GY. 
  11. During your opponent's draw phase, activate Sanctifire's effect to summon Big-Winged Berfomet to your field and D/D Orthros to your opponent's field. 
  12. CL1 (mandatory effect) D/D Orthros to lock your opponent out of special summoning anything except fiends, CL2 Big-Winged Berfomet to search for level 4 beast + Chimera Fusion to hand. 
This combo is particularly nasty since it is well protected and hard to interrupt with handtraps. Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts makes fiend and beast floodgates very searchable, while Branded Fusion allows the deck to summon from GY a lingering floodgate to your opponent's field while summoning a resource generator to yours. Your opponent can't play while you amass resources for OTK next turn! 
 
The Chimera engine can search out Branded Fusion to start your Branded strategy! 
 
Mirror Swordknight = Search for Branded Fusion.
  1. Normal summon Mirror Swordknight. 
  2. Activate Mirror Swordknight's effect to summon Big-Winged Berfomet from deck.
  3. On summon, Big-Winged Berfomet searches for Chimera Fusion and Springans Kitt from deck. 
  4. Normal summon Springans Kitt. 
  5. Springans Kitt searches for Branded Fusion from deck. 
The Branded Engine can search for Mirror SwordKnight to initiate your Chimera strategy!
 
Branded Fusion = Search for Mirror Swordknight.
  1. Activate Branded Fusion, summoning Rindbrumm using Albaz + Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws. 
  2. Gazelle the King of Mythical Claw's effect activates when used as fusion material to search for any illusion monster. Add Cornfield Coatl from deck. 
  3. Discard Cornfield Coatl to add Mirror Swordknight from deck. 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Branded Fusion makes greats Ash bait! For once, it's okay for Branded Fusion to get ash'd since your main strategy is with your Chimera cards! 
  • Dimensional Barrier absolutely demolishes this deck. Oftentimes, the only counter to a blow-out like this is Triple Tactics Thrust so you can set a card to skip your opponent's turn in retaliation. 
  • Droll and Lockbird usually stops this strategy since it needs multiple searches per turn. Crossouts and Called by the Grave can be sided in games 2/3 to counteract this threat! Otherwise, using Branded Fusion to summon Mirrorjade may be the best option. 
  • When you assume your opponent will force you to play second, side out all your "floodgate" cards and enablers from your deck for more boardbreakers and staples. 
  • This deck can comfortably play the powerful infamous floodgate "There Can Be Only One." When going first vs. a deck susceptible to it, side them in! 
  • Other floodgate targets for you to summon with Chimera Branded are: Barrier Statue of the Abyss (Dark Attribute lock), Chaos Hunter (Anti-Banish floodgate), and Koa'ki Meiru Doom (Anti-Light/Dark effects). If you're playing for time, you can summon Red Resonator to gain lifepoints. 
  • A gimmicky (since it isn't searchable) but powerful combo is available with Fusion Armament. Activate Armament revealing Naturia Exterio to special summon Naturia Beast (although its negated) from the Extra Deck. Go through your Chimera combo sending Farfa, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss to the GY to banish Naturia Beast until the End Phase. When it comes back during your End Phase, it won't be negated anymore!
  • If you have Crossout Designator and you're summoning Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts, you can easily summon any Fiend or Beast floodgate from deck. Activate Crossout, banishing your Fiend/Beast floodgate of choice. Go through Chimera combo and eventually send Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts to the GY. During your opponent's turn, banish Berfomet to summon your floodgate from the banished pile! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Ever since Branded came out about two and a half years ago, I've stayed with my beloved Branded cards and piloted nearly every incarnation of the deck. I believe the next evolution of Branded is with Chimera, an arguably even stronger fusion strategy! When mixed together, both archetypes make up for each other's weaknesses and boost each other to competitive power levels! The strategy's ability to play through interruption, amass resources, set-up powerful boards and insta-win games with searchable floodgates is incredible. it is safe to say that Branded Chimera is a meta competitior that is dangerously competent at top tier levels! 
 
Chimera's old-school retrains of Yugi's cards from DM also appeal to my "Yugi-Boomer" heart, so any deck it mixes well with is automatically extremely cool in my books. As an avid fan of Yugi's cards, I can only hope Chimera gets additional support in the future, whether direct or indirect. 
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Taking a look at Sorcerer of Dark Magic
deck_description:
I am not a fan of the Pyramid of Light movie, and I am an even less fan of Sorcerer of Dark Magic which debuted in the move as a counterpart to Blue-Eyes Shining Dragon. It is a Level 9 DARK Spellcaster monster that cannot be Normal Summoned or Set and must be Special Summoned from hand by Tributing 2 Level 6 or higher Spellcaster monster and cannot be Special Summoned by other ways. While face-up on field, whenever a Trap Card is activated, you can negate the activation and destroy it. This is not once per turn which equate Sorcerer of Dark Magic to basically infinite Trap Card negates. But then you realize, it is just a worse version of Jinzo. Jinzo prevents the activation of Trap Cards and effects on field and negates the effects of all Trap Cards on the field. Not only is Sorcerer of Dark Magic so incredibly convoluted to Summon, but its effect is godawful, doing even less than what Jinzo can do. And Jinzo has no restrictions on how it needs to be Summoned. This is the Level 9 monster that we are taking a look at today, and to be quite frank, I don't really know a very consistent way to search and Summon it outside of the new Supreme King cards from AGOV in conjuction with the existing Pendulum Magician cards. It is incredibly easy to get 2 copies of Supreme King Gate Magician out onto the field in your standard Supreme King Pendulum combo shenanigans, so that solves the issue of getting 2 Level 6 or higher Spellcaster monsters onto field to Special Summon Sorcerer of Dark Magic from hand. Now, how would you search it? Timestar Magician can detach an Xyz Material from itself to add a DARK Spellcaster monster from Deck, GY, or face-up Extra Deck to hand which means that it can search for Sorcerer of Dark Magic. Now, it's required materials are 2 Level 4 Pendulum Magician monsters. This is easily accomplished by Harmonizing Magician who can Special Summon a Pendulum Magician monster from Deck when it is Pendulum Summoned from hand, allowing you to choose from a plethora of potential monster to Summon, but I am electing to play Performapal Celestial Magician in this Deck as it is a Level 4 Pendulum Magician to overlay with our Level 4 Harmonizing Magician to go into Timestar Magician and since it can also give you the ability to search a Pendulum Monster during the End Phase for potential follow-up usages. Considering all that we have to go through to get to Sorcerer of Dark Magic, you may or may not draw World Legacy Monstrosity to help you go into your Aggregator send Herald line, but you still have the full capability of just playing Pendulum if you cannot access your Prediction Princess stuff. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down, and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during the End Phase. Tarotreith can either be Ritualed or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's End Phase effect. On flip, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down and she can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back if she is Tributed and sent to GY. On flip, she can add a Prediction Princess other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while face-up on field, she gives your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection from your opponent's effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates the activated effects of your opponent's monsters on their side of their field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can add a Level 9 from Deck to hand with a different Type and Attribute than it. 1 Sorcerer of Dark Magic. If you draw this card, it is not the end of the world. You can literally just make other Pendulum plays to get more interaction onto the field instead of having to go into Timestar Magician as you already have Sorcerer in hand. 1 Metalfoes Vanisher. This card's effects don't matter in this context. It's here because it's a Level 9 Pendulum Monster. In certain applications, it being a Pendulum Monster does come up like if you are trying to use it to make Exceed the Pendulum, and it is also Summonable off of World Legacy Monstrosity targeting Sorcerer of Dark Magic. 3 Supreme King Gate Magician. Its Scale effect allows you to pop it to place a Supreme King Gate Pendulum Monster other than itself in your Pend Zone. And it's monster effect allows you to send a Pendulum, Fusion, Synchro, or Xyz Dragon monster from hand or Extra Deck to GY to Special Summon itself from hand. And on Normal or Special Summon, it can add a card that mentions Supreme King Z-ARC from your Deck to your hand except for a Spellcaster monster. 1 Supreme King Gate Zero as a Scale 0 Supreme King Gate Pend Monster. 3 Supreme King Dragon Darkwurm which can Special Summon itself from GY if you control no monsters, and when it is Normal or Special Summoned, you can search for a Supreme King Gate Pend Monster from Deck. 1 Supreme King Dragon Lightwurm which is just a searchable Level 4 Tuner monster that is also a high scale. 2 Harmonizing Magician which can Special Summon a Pendulum Magician monster from your Deck other than itself with its effects negates when it is Pendulum Summoned. Again, Harmonizing gets you to another Level 4 Pend Magician to go into Timestar Magician. Now, you cannot use Harmonizing Magician for a Fusion, Synchro, or Xyz Summon unless all of the other materials are Pend Magicians, but that isn't too much of a problem as Harmonizing does get you a Pend Magician from Deck on Pendulum Summon. You can get Performapal Celestial Magician to either go into Timestar Magician or Borreload Savage Dragon depending on the situation, but it can get you Supreme King Gate Magician which gives you a Level 7 monster on field to go into Odd-Eyes Absolute Dragon or as addition Link Material if needed as Harmonizing does not restrict itself when it comes to Link Summons. 1 Performapal Celestial Magician which is our target in Deck for Harmonizing Magician. During your Main Phase the turn it was Normal or Special Summoned, you can apply the following effects based on what other monsters you control. Fusion gives it the ability to attack directly, Synchro prevents your opponent from activating monster effects for the rest of the turn, Xyz doubles its ATK, and Pendulum allows you to search a Pendulum Monster from Deck during the End Phase. 3 Diviner of the Herald. It sends a Fairy monster from your Deck or Extra Deck to the GY. It can send Herald of the Arc Light for a Ritual search or it can send Tarotrei or Tarotreith in case you want them in rotation to Ritual Summon via Underworld Ritual of Prediction.

Spell/Traps: 2 Wings of Light which searches a Supreme King Dragon or Supreme King Gate Pendulum Monster from Deck to hand during the Main Phase. 3 Dragon Shrine which we are using to dump Supreme King Dragon Darkwurm from Deck. 1 Foolish Burial. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 1 Instant Fusion to get to Master of Ham. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from Gy during the Standby Phase in order to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. And finally, 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can Special Summon a Level 9 from hand or target a Level 9 on field and Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with different Types and Attributes than the target on field but with different names.

Extra Deck: 1 Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon which can be Special Summoned via Odd-Eyes Absolute Dragon and it can target and return a face-up Attack Position monster your opponent controls to the hand, and you can shuffle a face-up Pend Monster in your Extra Deck into the Deck to negate and destroy an activated Spell/Trap or monster effect. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Borreload Savage Dragon which can equip a Link Monster from Gy to it on Synchro Summon to give itself Borrel Counters equal to that monster's Link Rating and you can remove 1 Borrel Counter from it to negate the activation of a card or effect of your opponent's. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand when sent to Gy. 1 Mereologic Aggregator which sends a monster from Extra Deck to Gy on Xyz Summon and target monsters in GY up to the number of its attached materials, detach the same number of materials, and attach those monsters in Gy to itself. 1 Odd-Eyes Absolute Dragon which can Special Summon an Odd-Eyes monster from Extra Deck if it is Xyz Summoned and sent to GY. 1 Odd-Eyes Rebellion Xyz Dragon which can detach an Xyz Material to target and destroy up to 2 monsters your opponent controls with 3000 ATK or less. And it is also a target to send to Summon Supreme King Gate Magician. 1 Timestar Magician which can detach an Xyz Material to add a DARK Spellcaster monster from Deck, Gy, or face-up Extra Deck to hand. That's pretty much all that we are using it for. 1 Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess. 1 Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians which places Spell Counters on itself equal to the number of Spells on field and in Gy on Link Summon and you can remove 3 Spell Counters to Special Summon a Spellcaster monster from hand or Gy in Defense Position to a zone it points to. 1 Exceed the Pendulum which can add a Pendulum Monster from your Extra Deck to your hand on Link Summon, and during the Main Phase, you can Quick Effect Special Summon a Pendulum Monster from your hand or GY whose Level is between your Scales. 1 Beyond the Pendulum which can Pay 1200 on Link Summon to add a Pendulum Monster from your Deck to your hand, but you cannot activate monster effects or scale effects until you Pendulum Summon, and if you Pendulum Summon 2 monsters with different names to the zones it points to you can target and destroy 2 cards on field. And finally, 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 I:P Masquerena. 

Side Deck: 3 Thunder King, the Lightingstrike Kaiju, 1 Kurikara Divincarnate, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Lightning Storm, 1 Harpie's Feather Duster, 3 Evenly Matched, and 3 Infinite Impermanence.

Dark Magician Deck + Side Deck

(November 2023)
A deck that I'm using in locals, It's a lot of fun . Where do you think I need improve it?

The first thing you might notice is why the hell are you playing droplet with shifter and macro cosmos.  lol.  I dont have a good answer for that, but if you're under d fissure it still works, just gotta send a spell/trap.  If you don't have shifter/fissure/macro cosmos it's Droplet and you know what that does, but honestly my real answer was that I didn't quite know what else to put in.  Maybe veiler?  3 droll main?  Not sure, it's definitely a flex spot.

One Sakitama, cuz I found myself bricking on 2 and that never feels good, thinking about maybe adding a third Aratama, but I find these ratios pretty nice so far.

Went 2 - 1 at locals last night, loss was to Mannadium and I didn't see any of my shifters or d fissure and got Nib'd game 1.

Exosister is now a pretty nice budget rogue deck due to all the decks that need their grave and when you get the nonstop banishing from Magnifica -> Mikalis -> Returnia banish 2 its so godlike.  Obviously you don't have to play S:P or Thrust, but they are nice if you have them.  Downerd does nothing and is a completely dead card, just didn't take it out-- it could be anything else like Knightmare Phoenix or another good link or rank 4.  The main deck exosisters are spellcasters, could play Selene and Accesscode as well.  I'm not on Utopic Draco because Martha turns that line off, but it is something you can do.

I also was trying the dinomorphia variant and it can be very good, but you have to make sure you perform your exosister plays before you can bring out Rexterm I.E.: Exosister Returnia can only be used if you control ONLY exosister monsters.  If you want to do all your banishing, that leaves you with the opportunity to summon Rexterm later in your opponents term, meaning that you have a choice to make: let your opponent try to establish a board and try to break it with your Exosisters, or get Rexterm out ASAP to try and establish the floodgate early.  Doing this turns off Returnia until Rexterm leaves the board.

Anyway, just take out the Downerd, maybe change out droplet for another good handtrap or board breaker and you're golden.

Libromancer Mereologic Deck Master Duel

https://youtu.be/Uo1u5yVp9Uc

Exodius? Venus? Transmodify? Shine Balls? What are you talking about? We out here in 2023 playing Prediction Princess in World Chalice. The Level 9 monster that we are taking a look at today is World Chalice Guardragon Almarduke, the good counterpart to a fellow Level 9 monster, World Legacy Guardragon Mardark. Almarduke is a Level 9 WIND Dragon monster which is a good target on field for World Legacy Monstrosity, but we aren't playing Monstrosity in this Deck. You definitely could, but I feel like it limits you way too much. If you were playing Monstrosity and were actively relying on it, you will be ending on absolutely nothing if you don't draw it. Think about what a World Chalice endboard looks like: Tri-Gate Wizard, an Apollousa with some number of negates, Firewall Dragon (?), maybe an Extra Link? Do you really think that we can accomplish all of that considering that almost half of our Deck is dedicated to Prediction Princess plays? This Deck plays similar to Sigrun Prediction Princess where your entire combo focuses on Diviner of the Herald. But in this case, you need both access to a Normal Monster on field without using your Normal Summon and Diviner of the Herald. Your Normal Monster goes into Imduk the World Chalice Dragon while you Normal Summon Diviner, sending Trias Hierarchia from Deck to GY. Hierarchia tributes Diviner to Summon itself from GY, and Diviner activates as it was Tributed to Special Summon Lee the World Chalice Fairy from your Deck. Lee triggers on Special Summon to add a World Legacy - "World Chalice" from Deck to hand. Using your extra Normal Summon from Imduk, you Tribute Lee to Tribute Summon World Chalice. At this point, you can send a monster from hand to add Lee back from GY. Then, you Link off World Chalice and Imduk for Auram the World Chalice Blademaster. You could go into any Link-2 but all of the World Chalice Link Monsters can Special Summon a World Chalice Monster from hand if sent from field to GY which can give you more material. If you have a World Chalice in hand or added back Lee, Imduk can Special Summon that monster from hand. And World Chalice activates to Special Summon 2 World Chalice monsters from Deck which can be any 2 monsters as long as 1 of them is World Chalice Guardragon (if you didn't draw it). Coincidentally, you can chain block World Chalice with Imduk, so that is also a positive. Next, you can Link off your World Chalice monster and World Chalice Guardragon to go into any Link-2, but let's say Lib the World Key Blademaster in this situation. Lib can set World Legacy Succession from Deck and it can be activated since World Legacy - "World Chalice" is currently in GY. (Note: If you set World Legacy Monstrosity with Lib's effect, it cannot be activated even if you have World Legacy monster in GY because it's a Quick-Play Spell.) You can then activate Succession to bring back any monster from GY to Linkpoint for extra material on field. Next, you can banish World Chalice Guardragon from GY to Special Summon a Normal Monster in GY in Defense to Linkpoint. Next, you Link off that Normal Monster for another Imduk the World Chalice Dragon, giving you your 3rd Link Monster on field. You can now Tribute Auram the World Chalice Blademaster, Lib the World Key Blademaster, and Imduk the World Chalice Dragon to Special Summon World Chalice Guardragon Almarduke from Extra Deck, giving you your second Level 9 monster on field. Next, you overlay Almarduke and Hierarchia on field to make Mereologic Aggregator which sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY for a Ritual search. Aggregator then targets Herald in GY, detaching 1 material to attach Herald from GY to itself. Link off Aggregator and the monster you previously Special Summoned back from GY with World Legacy Succession to go into I:P Masquerena. Herald hits the GY again for another Ritual search. You do need to have access to either 1 Ritual Spell, 1 Ritual Monster, or a Bibliomuse to go through the whole combo, but that is very likely with the ratios that we are playing in this Deck. So yeah, that is the convoluted combo to get to a Prediction Princess combo using World Chalice cards. It surprisingly is not that difficult to pull off, and it works quite well. Is the investment worth it? Probably not. But who is going to actually play World Chalice Prediction Princess anyways. This is just me experimenting with different Level 9's. 

Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY during the End Phase. Tarotreith can be Ritualed or Special Summoned with Tarotrei. On flip, it can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down and it can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Summon itself back from GY if it is Tributed and sent there. On flip, it can add a Prediction Princess monster other than itself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand, and while face-up on field, it gives your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection from your opponent's effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates the activated effects of all monsters on your opponent's field after it has been flipped face-up, and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 with a different Type and Attribute than it. 1 Trias Hierarchia which can Tribute a Fairy to Special Summon itself from hand or GY. 3 Diviner of the Herald which can send a Fairy monster from Deck or Extra Deck to GY on Normal or Special Summon, and if it is Tributed, you can Special Summon a Levle 2 or lower Fairy from hand or Deck except for itself which gets you to Lee the World Chalice Fairy in this Deck. For the World Chalice monsters: 1 Beckoned by the World Chalice, 3 Chosen by the World Chalice, 3 World Legacy - "World Chalice", 3 Lee the World Chalice Fairy, and 1 World Chalice Guardragon. Beckoned and Chosen are your Normal Monsters in this Deck. Beckoned can realistically be any Level 4 or lower Normal Monster in the game, but I am opting to play a World Chalice name just in case you draw it as you can Special Summon it from hand by the effect of a World Chalice Link Monster when its sent from field to GY. Chosen is a Psychic monster which means that you can go into it with Emergency Teleport which is a way for you to access a Normal Monster without using your Normal Summon. World Chalice can Tribute itself if a monster is Special Summoned from the Extra Deck to send that monster to the GY. We aren't actually using this effect because it isn't sticking on the field usually. But if you bring it back with World Legacy Succession in the combo I mentioned earlier, you can keep it on field, and instead, Xyz Summon Aggregator into the EMZ to Link it off for Gravity Controller after you've done your Herald shenanigans. You don't get the ability to go into I:P Masquerena for an S:P Little Knight on your opponent's turn, but it is an alternative play you can do, especially if you banish I:P or S:P for Prosperity. But more importantly, if this face-up Normal Summoned/Set card leaves the field, it can Special Summon 2 World Chalice monsters from Deck. You are always using it for this effect to extend your combo, and to get necessary World Chalice names out of the Deck into rotation like Guardragon for example. Lee can add a World Chalice monster from Deck to hand on Normal or Special Summon. You are always searching for World Chalice unless you already have it in hand, and if that is the case, then you can add any World Chalice name to hand as it really does not matter after that. And if it is in GY, you can send a monster from hand or field to GY to add it back to hand. This is actually very important as you need World Chalice monsters in hand if you want to make the most out of your World Chalice Link Monsters as they all can Special Summon a World Chalice monster from hand when sent from field to GY with it not being once per turn. World Chalice Guardragon has 1 effect that we are focusing on, and that is its GY effect. You can banish it from GY to target a Normal Monster in GY and Special Summon it in Defense to a Zone a Link Monster points to. This getting you a Normal Monster is how you are always accessing your 2nd Imduk the World Chalice Dragon for your 3rd Link Monster for Almarduke. You only need 1 because it is searchable off of Lee if you already have World Chalice in hand and World Chalice can Special Summon it straight from Deck. 

Spell/Traps: 1 World Legacy Succession which Special Summons a monster in GY to a zone a Link Monster points to. You can search this off of Lib the World Key Blademaster, but drawing it in your starting hand doesn't hurt as it is an extender that you didn't need to search for. 2 Unexpected Dai to Special Summon a Level 4 or lower Normal Monster from Deck if you control no monsters. I did say that you always want to have a way to get a Normal Monster onto field without using your Normal Summon. So why am I only playing 2 Dai? It's because it really hurts to draw 2 or more copies of it. We already are playing 3 copies of Emergency Teleport for the same usage, to get a Normal Monster onto the field without using our Normal Summon, and that does not have a restriction, nor is it once per turn. Also, we are playing 1 copy of Called by the Grave to have the potential to insulate ourselves against something like Ash Blossom or Droll, and if we were to cut something to play Called by, it would most likely be the 3rd Unexpected Dai eitherway. 3 Pot of Prosperity. It is good to have a chance of searching Diviner or a way to access a Normal Monster, especially through a card like Prosperity, but you do have to be careful about what you are banishing from your Extra Deck as were are playing a decent amount of cards necessary for our combo. Now, if you were to go with the First of the Dragons line to get an additional Level 9 onto the field, then, you wouldn't have to worry too much, but if were were to go for the World Chalice Guardragon Almarduke line, then, I would say otherwise. 1 Instant Fusion to access Master of Ham. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. And finally, 3 Infinite Impermanence. And when it comes to World Legacy Monstrosity, I am not playing it, but that doesn't mean that you shouldn't play it. You can play 1 copy in case you draw it and it targeting Almarduke gives you a lot of material to work for, but I guess you would have to adjust your Extra Deck a little bit to include Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity to have more Rank 9 options to go into for interruption.

Extra Deck: 1 World Chalice Guardragon Almarduke which requires 3 Link Monsters as Fusion Material, but you can also Tribute the Fusion Materials from your field to Special Summon it from your Extra Deck. It's effect really doesn't matter much, but I guess it is somewhat relevant that it can attack all monsters your opponent controls once each, and that is not bad, especially with it having 3000 orignal ATK. 1 First of the Dragons which needs to be Fusion Summoned with 2 Normal Monsters and cannot be Special Summoned by other ways. It's unaffected by other monster's effects and it cannot be destroyed by battle except with a Normal Monster. It is a Level 9 DARK Dragon monster, and you can Fusion Summon it in this Deck with Proxy F Magician, so in case you can't get to Almarduke for some reason or don't feel like going into Almarduke for whatever reason, you can just finagle your combo to get 2 Normal Monsters on field along with Proxy F to Fuse into First of the Dragons to get your other Level 9 to overlay with Hierarchia to go into Aggregator. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell when sent to GY. 1 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 Proxy F Magician. It can Fusion Summon using monsters from your field as Fusion Material and if a Fusion Monster is Fusion Summoned to a Zone it points to, it can Special Summon a monster with 1000 or less ATK from hand. 1 Knightmare Phoenix. 1 Auram the World Chalice Blademaster which needs 2 World Chalice monsters, and its effect on field really doesn't matter, but it can Special Summon a World Chalice monster from hand when its sent from field to GY. 1 Lib the World Key Blademaster which can only be Link Summoned while you have a World Legacy card in GY and you can set a World Legacy Spell/Trap from Deck but it cannot be activated this turn unless you have a World Legacy monster in GY. You will have a World Legacy monster in GY in this Deck in World Chalice, and you will always be getting Succession as an extender. 2 Imduk the World Chalice Dragon which needs a Normal Monster as material and it gives you an extra Normal Summon of a World Chalice monster once per turn, and it Special Summons a World Chalice monster from hand when sent from field to GY. Finally, 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, 1 Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit, 1 Droll & Lock Bird, 2 Crossout Designator, 2 Dark Ruler No More, and 3 Evenly Matched.

I'm going to stick with the theme that Joey's deck is the most underdeveloped deck in the series. I like this version of Joey's deck. He now has the Red-Eyes Black Dragon. Currently what I'm running for my Z-Arc deck, the hand traps and side deck are constantly changing with this current format but the rest of the deck is fairly standard.

I reduced the size of the harmonizing package as going into baronne off it is always the best option and it allows for an easy siding pattern for swapping it out when going second or the match up it doesn't do that much in.

Without electrumite selene and exceed are both needed because they both serve the purpose of turning the trap online and also summoning gate magician on your oponnents turn to add follow up is one of reasons this deck is by far the best pend deck at the moment. It feels good to have a pend deck that is playable and doesn't get blown out as badly by having no non engine space and it also is super consistent while still always being a 2 card, there's a combination of  20+ cards if you open them together it's full combo, so you can draw 2 starters/ extenders and 3 hand traps and be able to play to full combo. 

The deck does loose badly to droll with most hands but it can play around nib and stuff if you play to a weaker end board which is normally only setting up the trap with gate magician on field but a board nuke is enough against some decks and with hand traps in hand it makes it even better. S:P little knight is also insane in this deck adds an extra layer of interaction as an option to the end board which makes it even better. The deck does loose to droll, nib, dshifter like every pend deck but it's by far the most consistent pend deck to play.

deck_description:
Branded Despia is the ultimate lore-based meta deck centering around our hero - Albaz! Fusion summon your way to victory with gigantic Dragons while plusing to infinity and beyond during your own turn AND your opponent's turn!

This is the usual Branded Despia list I've been playing - except I've taken out the Edge Imp package and put in the TTThrust package. Fun fact, TTThrust can search Branded Fusion! I've also included into it "Fusion Duplication," another Thrust target that can copy Branded Fusion's effect in the graveyard so you can further fuse in your opponent's turn!

deck_excerpt: ygoprodeck.com, yugipedia.com, yugioh.fandom.com, yugiohtopdecks.com, ygorganization.com, rushcard.io, discordapp.com/discord.gg, imgur.com,
deck_description: Branded Chimera

On my quest of slapping every Level 9 monster into Prediction Princess, today we arrive at Gold Pride - Pin Baller, a Level 9 DARK Machine Fusion Monster. The second wave of Gold Pride support that also brought along Pin Baller surprisingly can be easily fitted into the main engine cards that I used for my Master of Ham Prediction Princess Deck. This is all thanks in part to Gold Pride - Chariot Carrie who is a generic Rank 3 monster that can be made with Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra. Chariot Carrie can search our next Gold Pride card, Gold Pride - Better Luck Next Time!, which searches our final Gold Pride card, Gold Price - Roller Baller, reducing our Life Points by its ATK, allowing us to Summon it to the field and fuse with Chariot Carrie into Pin Baller for a Level 9 target on field for World Legacy Monstrosity. Keep in mind that this is in addition to Cobra having already searched for Instant Fusion to get Master of Ham for Prediction Princess Bibliomuse, so in the case where you already have your Ritual pieces, you can also end on a Quick Fusion into Pin Baller as well to have it equip your opponent's monsters for more disruption. I still think that something like Ham Prediction Princess is a much better Deck, but for it being relatively easy to incorporate it into Ham Prediction Princess and it working to a degree, it still has some merit to it. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotreith and 1 Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Tarotreith can be Ritual Summoned or Summoned from hand or GY via Tarotrei's End Phase effect. On Flip, it can Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down and as a Quick Effect, it can Flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Tarotrei can Quick Effect Flip a monster face-up or face-down and can Summon a Flip Monster from hand or Gy in face-down Defense Position during the End Phase. 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse which on Flip adds a Prediction Princess monster other than itself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand. If it's Tributed and sent to GY, it can Summon itself back face-down, and while on field, it gives your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates all of your opponent's monsters' activated effects on field after it has been flipped face-up, and when it's destroyed on field, it can add a Level 9 with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck to hand. 1 Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light which is a Level 9 that adds a Plant monster or Generaider card from Deck to hand on Summon. Just like in my Ham Prediction Princess Deck, Mardel is a Level 9 that you can get off of both Lonefire Blossom and World Legacy Monstrosity. You could play Impcantation Talismandra instead as a Plant that can be Summoned off of Lonefire and that could also search a Ritual Monster from Deck on Special Summon from the Deck, but I like playing Mardel more. Moving onto the Gold Pride monsters, we are playing 2 Gold Pride - Roller Baller and 1 Gold Pride - Captain Carrie. The more important card here is Roller Baller. If your Life Points are lower than your opponent’s, you can Special Summon it from your hand, and as a Quick Effect during the Main Phase, you can Fusion Summon a Gold Pride Fusion Monster by using monsters from your hand and/or field as material. Realistically, you only need the 1 Roller Baller for your combo, but you have to search it with Gold Pride - Better Luck Next Time! in order to lower your Life Points. If you don’t lower your Life Points by Better Luck Next Time’s searching effect, you can’t get Roller Baller onto the field if you hard drew the 1 copy, so it is better to play 2 to have 1 in Deck just in case you do draw 1 of your copies in your starting hand. Captain Carrie is more or less in the Deck for two main reasons. The first reason is that she can act as a Small World Bridge from something like Ash Blossom to Carrie to Scorpio, Carrie to Roller Baller to Bibliomuse, or Ash Blossom to Carrie to Lonefire. The second reason is that Gold Pride - Chariot Carrie has a mandatory effect to return herself to the Extra Deck if she used her first effect to add a Gold Pride Spell/Trap from Deck to hand, Summoning a Captain Carrie from Deck or GY to replace herself. This is especially important when you are trying to use Roller Baller to Fuse into Pin Baller on your opponent’s turn for interruption. You need Roller Baller in addition to another Gold Pride monster to make Pin Baller, and what you would usually do is Fuse Chariot Carrie and Roller Baller. And with Chariot Carrie booting herself during the End Phase, you need access to another Gold Pride Monster to Fuse which is why we are playing Captain Carrier. 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra. Scorpio discards a monster to Special Summon a Predaplant from Deck and when Cobra is Special Summoned by the effect of a Predaplant monster, you can add a Poly or Fusion Spell from Deck to hand. You are going to be searching Instant Fusion in order to get to Master of Ham for Bibliomuse. 2 Lonefire Blossom which can Tribute a Plant, usually being itself, to Summon a Plant from Deck. This gets you Scorpio from Deck to get to Cobra, then, getting you to Instant Fusion. But you can also get Mardel like how I mentioned earlier to get a Level 9 target on field for Monstrosity. 3 Diviner of the Herald to send a Fairy from Deck or Extra Deck to GY on Summon, being usually Herald of the Arc Light for a Ritual search. In a situation where you don’t have access to Scorpio, you really need a way to get Ritual searches in order to have some resemblance of a play rather than passing on nothing. And finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring.

For the Spell/Traps: 1 Gold Pride - Better Luck Next Time! which adds a Gold Pride monster from Deck to hand on activation and you lose Life Points equal to its ATK. That is pretty much all that we are using the card for. This card searches Roller Baller from Deck and lowers your Life Points which allows you to get said Roller Baller out onto the field to Fuse into Pin Baller. 3 Small World for searching. 1 Instant Fusion to get out Master of Ham from the Extra Deck for Bibliomuse access. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from hand or target a Level 9 monster on field and Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters with different names with a different Type and Attribute than the targeted monster. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from your hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase in order to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 3 Pot of Prosperity and 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster.  

Extra Deck: 1 Gold Pride - Pin Baller. This requires Gold Pride - Roller Baller and 1 or more additional Gold Pride monsters as Fusion Material. If it is Fusion Summoned, you can equip face-up monsters your opponent controls up to the number of Fusion Materials used for its Fusion Summon to it, and if your Life Points are lower than your opponent’s, this effect’s activation and effect cannot be negated. You usually don’t need to use this effect of Pin Baller if you are Summoning it on your first turn to get a Level 9 monster onto the field as a target for World Legacy Monstrosity. However, in a situation where you do draw your Ritual Prediction Princess pieces and are able to do your whole combo or some assemblance of your combo to end on sufficient interruption, you can keep your Gold Pride - Roller Baller and your Gold Pride - Chariot Carrie that tags out into Gold Pride - Captain Carrie on the field so that Roller Baller can Quick Effect Fusion Summon Pin Baller to actually use this effect as a form of non-negatable interruption which is really good. If  you activate this effect, you do have to return it to the Extra Deck and Special Summon Roller Baller from Deck or GY during the End Phase, but it usually is not sticking around for long enough for this to be wholly relevant. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down on Fusion Summon, which gets you to Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand when sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 1 Mereologic Aggregator which sends a monster from your Extra Deck to the GY on Xyz Summon and you can target monsters in your GY up to the number of materials attached to it, detach the same number of materials, and attach the targeted monsters from GY to it. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Gold Pride - Chariot Carrie. Chariot Carrie can detach a material to search for a Gold Pride Spell/Trap from Deck, and if your Life Points are lower than your opponent’s you can also send a Gold Pride monster from your Deck to your GY. There is only 1 Gold Pride Spell in the Deck for you to search off of Chariot Carrie and that is Gold Pride - Better Luck Next Time. And it is not like you need to dump a Gold Pride monster either because this isn’t a Gold Pride Deck per say. We are only using Gold Pride as a medium to get a Level 9 on field for Monstrosity. During the End Phase, if you activated this effect, Chariot Carrier returns herself to Extra Deck to Special Summon a Gold Pride - Captain Carrie from Deck or GY. This doesn’t come up much, but if you are planning to Fusion Summon Pin Baller on your opponent’s turn for interruption, Chariot Carrie is forced to return herself to replace herself with Captain Carrie during the End Phase either way and it keeps a Gold Pride on field to use as Fusion Material for Pin Baller. 1 Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess, 1 Cross-Sheep, 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 3 Triple Tactics Thrust, 2 Triple Tactics Talent, 1 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Evenly Matched, and 1 Dimensional Barrier.

deck_excerpt: Test Deck, Clear Effector, Chaos Angel, Labrynth
deck_description: While looking online for light, potentially fiend monsters that can be used to summon Chaos angel so it gets its secondary effect I found the card Clear Effector. Looking at it objectively it seems that it wouldn't be good for other decks until you consider that Chaos Angel doesn't really need a tuner to summon it. Additionally, Clear Effector seems to help solve two of the biggest problems Labrynth seems to have, a lack of cards in hand and Chaos Angel being popped on your opponents turn. The strategy is to bring out Big or Lovely then normal Clear Effector and suddenly your Chaos Angel is a much more menacing threat turn 0. Let me know what you think!

deck_excerpt: My first speed duel deck XD.

deck_description: Stardust Synchro
Purrely go BRRRRR

This deck has taken a bit of time and testing to get right but as of now it works very consistently and leaves you with a very powerfull end board. For full combo (without getting interrupted) all you need in the starting hand is access to a live twin monster (other then frost or treat) and access to an unchained trap. With this you should be able to end on Evil★Twin Trouble Sunny, Unchained Soul of Rage, D/D/D Wave High King Caesar and whatever trap you started with. You can potentially have Linguriboh up if you have a live☆twin in hand as well as frost or treat in hand to overcome evenly matched. If you're opponent is running monster destruction cards like lightning storm and raigeki then you can summon muckracker to the field during the combo to protect your cards however, you won't be able to set a trap is you choose this option.

Combo 1 (Regular Combo):

Step 1: First you are gonna want to do your twin combo up Trouble Sunny (I would recommend not drawing with Ki-sikil unless you have to incase your opponent is playing droll and lock bird).

Step 2: Use Trouble Sunny effect to bring back both Evil★Twins Lil-la and Ki-sikil and link them into Unchained Soul Lord of Yama. Use Yama's summon effect to search Unchained Twins - Aruha.

Step 3: Set your unchained trap and use Aruha effect to destroy it and special summon itself to the field. On resolution use the unchained trap effect to special summon Unchained Twins - Sarama to the field.

Step 4: Use Sarama effect to set the unchained trap from the grave and destroy Aruha. Next, use Aruha effect to special summon Unchained Soul of Shyama to the field.

Step 5: Link Shyama and Yama into Unchained Soul of Rage. Then use Shyama effect from the grave to destroy Sarama and special summon itself to the field. On resolution, use Sarama effect to special summon Unchained Soul of Sharvara from the deck and use Yama effect at the same time to special summon Trouble Sunny from the grave.

Step 6: Overlay Shyama and Sharvara into D/D/D Wave High King Caesar and that is your setup.

 

Combo 2 (Linguriboh):

Its the same combo as before but after summoning your live twin to special summon its counter part from the deck, your special summon either frost or treat from hand, link into Linguriboh and carry on the combo as normal.

 

Combo 3 (Muckracker):

Carry on the normal combo up to adding Aruha to hand. Use aruha effect as normal to special summon itself to the field and special summon Sarama from the trap effect. Then you want to link Aruha and Yama into Muckracker. Once you have done that you then want to use Sarama effect to set Aruha and then destroy Aruha. This will trigger Aruha's effect to special summon Shyama from deck and Yama effect to special summon Trouble Sunny from grave. You then want to use Shyama effect on field to destroy Sarama which will activate Sarama's effect to special summon Sharvara from the deck. You then want to link these two into Unchained Soul of Rage and use Sharvara's effect to set the other trap card that you haven't used this turn (this part is very important). After that you want to use Shyama's effect from grave to special summon itself to the field by destroying that new set trap card. On resolution you want to use the trap card effect to special summon another Sharvara and then overlay into your D/D/D monster.

 

If you do choose to use this deck or a version of it please let me know how it performs as it has been doing very well for me atm.

This is a deck based off the Fire King archetype. I love the names of these cards and with the new support, I am sure they are much more playable. Enjoy!
DW

Playing Style

"Yubel" monsters share the common effect that they cannot be destroyed by battle and the controller does not take any battle damage from battles involving them. Also, when an Attack Position "Yubel" monster is attacked by an opponent's monster, before damage calculation, they take damage equal to that monster's ATK. When using the more powerful monsters of the archetype, the latter effect also triggers when the "Yubel" monster battles and is also able to remove the opponent's battling monster from the field.

The archetype's original strategy was to have the original "Yubel" monsters being destroyed which triggered their effects that trigger to Special Summon the more powerful forms of "Yubel"; destroying the original "Yubel" allows the Special Summon of "Yubel - Terror Incarnate", which can destroy other monsters on the field during each turn. Making "Terror Incarnate" leave the field enables "Yubel - The Ultimate Nightmare" to be Summoned, which can battle an opponent's monster, inflict damage and destroy them. The effects of "Yubel" monsters discouraged the opponent from trying to deal with them by battle, let alone Summoning their monsters in the first place, making them useful for stalling. However, the strategy was not a threat throughout the game's history due to the limited number of viable choices that could Summon the original three "Yubel" monsters. "The Ultimate Nightmare" lacks additional protection or a floating effect upon its destruction, forcing the player to go through the original "Yubel" and "Terror Incarnate" again in order to Special Summon "The Ultimate Nightmare" again.

In Phantom Nightmare, the archetype has received its first wave of support that aided the archetype's original strategy. "Samsara Regenerating Lotus" can Tribute itself to Special Summon a "Yubel" monster from the Deck while if left alone on the field, it can make any monster effect into destroying a "Yubel" monster on the field, making it easier to trigger the destruction effects of the "Yubel" monsters. It is able to recur itself from the GY to make use of its effects constantly each turn. "Geist Grinder Golem" can reveal a "Yubel" monster to Special Summon itself to the opponent's field while Special Summoning the revealed monster. If "Geist Grinder Golem" battles its opponent's "Yubel", the opponent (mainly the card's original owner) gains 3000 LP. While both of these monsters can Special Summon the original "Yubel", the optimal "Yubel" monster to Special Summon is "Spirit of Yubel", which upon being Special Summoned, it can search a Spell/Trap card that mentions "Yubel". Upon its destruction, "Spirit of Yubel" can also Special Summon the original "Yubel".

"Nightmare Pain" can destroy a DARK monster to add another support card for "Yubel" (thus triggering the destruction effects of "Yubel" monsters) and force all of the opponent's monsters to attack a "Yubel" monster. It also makes the opponent take battle damage from battles involving "Yubel" monsters which is independent of the "Yubel" monsters' shared effects of inflicting effect damage when they are attacked/battled, essentially making the opponent take damage double of their monster's ATK. "Mature Chronicle" makes use of Chronicle Counters earned from Special Summoning "Yubel" or its related monsters to either revive "Yubel", recur a banished card, banish a card from the Deck, destroy a card on the field, or even search "Super Polymerization". The archetype features a new boss Fusion Monster, "Yubel - Das Ewig Liebe Wächter", whose generic materials makes it a prime choice for Fusion Summoning with "Eternal Favorite" or "Super Polymerization" to clear away the opponent's monsters. It now gains effect destruction immunity in addition to battle destruction immunity and upon battling an opponent's monster, it can banish said monster after damaging them.

One method to quickly Fusion Summon "Yubel - Das Ewig Liebe Wächter" by using the opponent's monsters requires only "Samsara Regenerating Lotus" and any other card in hand. "Samsara Regenerating Lotus" can Tribute itself to Special Summon "Spirit of Yubel" from the Deck, which can add "Nightmare Pain" to the hand. Next, "Nightmare Pain" can destroy "Spirit of Yubel" to add "Eternal Favorite" to the hand, while triggering "Spirit of Yubel" to Summon the original "Yubel" from the Deck. After Setting "Eternal Favorite", "Samsara Regenerating Lotus" can Special Summon itself during the End Phase, and be Tributed by "Yubel" to keep itself on the field. At any moment during the opponent's turn, "Eternal Favorite" can be activated by discarding a card and Fusion Summon "Yubel - Das Ewig Liebe Wächter" using "Yubel" and all of the opponent's monsters.

While various staples can send "Yubel" monsters to the GY in preparation of Special Summoning them later, the most notable outsider cards for supporting the archetype's playstyle are the "Sacred Beasts" cards like "Dark Beckoning Beast" and "Opening of the Spirit Gates", which is able to revive "Yubel" or "Spirit of Yubel" and return all from the GY to the hand (such as "Nightmare Pain" and "Mature Chronicle") while the player controls a Level 10 monster.
Whoohoo

Y'know, if Krawler Soma was at the very least classified as a Flip Monster, then, we could just play Spirit of the Fall Wind to search for it and already have a target on field for Soma to flip face-down. End of story. But it isn't so we actually have to draw Soma or get it through Pot of Prosperity because World Legacy Survivor, despite it being a way to potentially search for a Krawler card, locks you into Link Monsters from the Extra Deck for the rest of the turn which is something you do not want in this Deck. Either way, here is Krawler Prediction Princess. It's not my most favorite out of Prediction Princess variants because of how awful it is to have to rely on having to draw Krawler Soma because there is no in-archetype card that we can play to actually search it without some kind of restriction that hinders our plays. It might seem a bit hypocritical of me to actually say this when some of my Prediction Princess lists have you entirely reliant on World Legacy Monstrosity when it also cannot be searched in-archetype. However, most of my Prediction Princess lists are just me experimenting with different Level 9 monsters. I am not actually trying to convince anyone to play Amazoness Prediction Princess, Infernoid Prediction Princess, Code Talker Prediction Princess, Dragonmaid Prediction Princess, etc. But some of them surprisingly are very capable of getting 2 Level 9’s on field without Monstrosity like Ancient Gear Prediction Princess, Fluffal Prediction Princess, Virtual World Prediction Princess, World Chalice Prediction Princess, and others. Krawler Prediction Princess is also capable of getting 2 Level 9 monsters on field without Monstrosity, but it relies solely on you drawing Soma which you either need to draw or find off of Prosperity with there nothing in between. I guess you could say that the Level 9 monster we are looking at today is Ultimate Great Insect because Deus-X Krawler is already a mainstay in Prediction Princess Decks and needs no introductions. Ultimate Great Insect released in Photon Hypernova alongside cards you can basically generalize as Giant Ballpark support. It's a Fusion Monster that requires a Level 8 Insect monster and a Level 7 Insect monster, but it can also be Special Summoned from Extra Deck by Tributing an Insect monster with 2000 or more DEF that's equipped with an Equip Card. And that's where Krawler Soma and Inzektor Picofalena come into play. Soma has a natural 2500 DEF stat and Picofalena can discard a card on Link Summon to equip another Insect monster with an Insect monster from Deck. This turns Soma into an Insect you can Tribute to Summon out Ultimate Great Insect. We are playing Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown which is an Insect you can equip to Soma from Deck. And when you Tribute Soma with Beargram equipped, now that Beargram is in GY, it can Special Summon itself from GY by banishing 3 other Insects from hand and/or GY, being the 3 Krawlers you have in GY currently. This gives you potential Rank 9 plays to go into Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows depending on what your hand looks like, or you can use it for more Link Material. Again, this isn’t my most favorite variant of Prediction Princess (that has to go to Predaplant Prediction Princess or Runick Prediction Princess), but I can’t deny the ability of this Deck to make a Rank 9 very easily in order to go through Prediction Princess plays and potentially end on another Rank 9.

Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei and 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith. Tarotrei is a Quick Effect to either flip a monster face-up or face-down and during the End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY in face-down Defense Position. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's End Phase effect. On Flip, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down and as a Quick Effect, she can flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse who can Special Summon herself back face-down if she was Tributed and sent to the GY. On Flip, she can add a Prediction Princess monster except herself and any Ritual Spell from Deck to hand, and while she is face-up on field, your Ritual Monsters have targeting and destruction protection from your opponent's card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler who negates the activated effects of all monsters on your opponent's side of the field, and if it is destroyed on field by battle or card effect, it cam add a Level 9 monster with a differnet Type and Attribute than it from Deck to hand. 1 World Legacy Dragon Mardark which is basically a Level 9 whose Type and Attribute make it Summonable from Deck off of World Legacy Monstrosity if we target Tarotrei, Tarotreith, Trias Hierarchia or Ultimate Great Insect as it is a Level 9 WIND Dragon monster. And I guess the only relevant effect it has in this Deck is its effect when destroyed on field which is the same as Deus-X, adding a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck to hand. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which on Flip allows you to choose 1 of the following: Draw 2 cards, Return all Spell/Traps on the field to their owner’s hand, Destroy all monsters your opponent controls, or look at your opponent’s hand and choose a card to shuffle back into their Deck. 1 Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown. It is a Level 9 EARTH Insect Monster that must be Special Summoned from hand or GY by banishing 3 Insect and/or Plant monsters from hand and/or GY. This does mean you can’t Summon it off of Monstrosity, but I did explain earlier that it can act as a way to go into a Rank 9 if you equip it with Picofalena or be used as Link Material. It also prevents your opponent from activating monster effects in response to the activation of your Spell/Trap Cards and effects which is definitely very nice in a Deck where we are playing things like World Legacy Monstrosity, Pre-Preparation of Rites, and Pot of Prosperity. Also, you can destroy all face-up monsters on the field during your Main Phase except for Insect and Plant monsters with Beargram not being able to attack directly for the rest of the turn. If you choose not to Summon it during your Turn 1, you can Summon it back from GY on Turn 3 and potentially attempt to clear the board if your opponent manages to go through your entire board on their previous turn. 1 Trias Hierarchia and 3 Diviner of the Herald. Hierarchia is also a valid Level 9 to get off of Monstrosity targeting Ultimate Great Insect, and you do have the ability to Tribute 1 Fairy on field to Summon it from hand or Gy which means that you can send it with Diviner and Summon it back to get a Level 9 on field for Monstrosity purposes. And it can also still Tribute Diviner even after it has been flipped face-down to Special Summon Soma from hand. Diviner sends a Fairy from Deck or Extra Deck to GY on Summon, increasing its Level by the same amount as that monster's Level. You usually send Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck for a Ritual search. For the Krawler monsters: 3 Krawler Soma, 1 Krawler Receptor and 1 Krawler Spine. Soma can target a face-up monster on field and flip that monster face-down to Summon itself from hand. On field, it can reduce its Level by 2 or 4 to Special Summon Krawler monsters with different names from your hand, Deck, or GY whose total combined Levels equal the amount you reduced Soma’s Level by in face-up or face-down Defense Position. Soma is obviously an incredibly good card, but at the same time, it is not that easily searchable, considering that we aren’t just playing Krawlers as a Deck and the fact that we cannot play World Legacy Survivor. Realistically, you only need to play 2 additional Krawler names, not including Deus-X Krawler because it’s a Level 9 so there is no way for Soma to Summon it, but you could play more names to have a greater variety of Flip Effect to choose from hypothetically. Receptor’s Flip Effect allows you to add a Krawler monster from Deck to hand while Spine’s Flip Effect allows you to target and destroy a monster on field. I guess your next best option in a Krawler name to play is Krawler Glial as its Flip Effect lets you Special Summon a Krawler from hand or GY in face-up Attack Position or face-down Defense Position. Finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring.

Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion to get to Master of Ham. 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which can only Ritual Summon Prediction Princess Tarotrei, and you can banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to search for a Prediction Princess monster. 2 World Legacy Monstrosity. We don’t need to actively rely on it in this Deck, but you can either choose to play 2 or 3 copies in the Deck. It can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from hand or target a Level 9 monster you control and Special Summon 2 Level 9 Monsters with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck with different names. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Infinite Impermanence.

Extra Deck: 1 Ultimate Great Insect which, again, can be Special Summoned from Extra Deck by Tributing an Insect Monster with 2000 or more DEF that’s equipped with an Equip Card. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck on Fusion Summon or when its flipped face-up, and you can banish 2 Flip Monsters from GY or face-up field to Special Summon it from GY face-down. Coincidentally, Soma Summoning 2 Krawlers gives you 2 Flip Monsters to banish from GY after you used them for Link Material to Summon Master of Ham which is definitely something. 2 Herald of the Arc Light to search for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell when its sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 1 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax, 1 S:P Little Knight, and 1 I:P Masquerena. I am choosing to play 1 Sky Striker Ace - Camellia over Subterror Behemoth Fiendess because I do not like Behemoth Fiendess in the slightest. Fiendess can send a Flip Monster from Deck to GY to Special Summon 1 monster from your hand in face-down Defense Position. I’ll be real with everyone: This is not a good effect for a Prediction Princess Deck. The only 3 Flip Decks that I can think of that actually benefit this effect is Tindangle, Subterror, and maybe Shaddoll (because the Flip Monster is sent from Deck to GY via an effect). Face-down monsters cannot be used as Link Material unless you are playing Ghostrick, and with a Deck like Prediction Princess that really needs its Zones and your whole set-up combo needing to Link Summon, this is not a very good monster to play. Yes, Fiendess does add a Flip Monster from Deck or GY to your hand if a monster it points to is flipped face-up which does get you a Bibliomuse potentially, but this effect is better for Subterror than it is for this Deck in specifics. Camellia is a generic Link Monster that, if sent to GY, you can target a monster your opponent controls, Special Summon this card to your opponent’s field, and send the targeted monster to the GY. I think that Linking off Camellia to go into a Little Knight or Avramax with Masquerena and having removal attached to it is way better than waiting for a niche situation where Behemoth Fiendess actually is viable. 1 Inzektor Picofalena which on Link Summon can discard a card to target another Insect you control and equip it with an Insect from Deck as an Equip Sell that gives it 500 ATK/DEF. This sets you up for Ultimate Great Insect which is great and you can also target 3 Insects in your GY, shuffle them into the Deck, and draw a card. This is nice for getting an additional card in hand during a turn where you haven’t used Prosperity. And finally, 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Kashtira Fenrir, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Triple Tactics Thrust, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, and 3 Evenly Matched.
